plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The medium-assisted field 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\textrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 [Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] arises from the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{m}}^{\parallel},\,T_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{f}}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 (solid box on the right), and the atomic Hamiltonian becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{at}}$
\end_inset

 via the PZW transformation [Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PZW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] (dashed box on the left).
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{at}}$
\end_inset

 interacts with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 thru 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\textrm{int}}$
\end_inset

 as in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:H_summarized"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 By neglecting the magnetic properties one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\textrm{int}}^{\textrm{dip}}$
\end_inset

, which completes the model investigated.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:model"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We start from a first-principle Hamiltonian where positive and negative
 charges of the atomic system and the medium are coupled with the electromagneti
c field.
 If the focus is on the atomic dynamics, the system can be conveniently
 modeled by coupling the atom to a 
\shape italic
medium-assisted
\shape default
 electromagnetic field, which is dressed by the interaction with the hosting
 medium (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Let us consider the Coulomb-gauge Hamiltonian
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogel2006,cohen1_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, separating the longitudinal and transverse contributions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
H=V_{\text{at}}^{\mathrm{\parallel}}+V_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{\parallel}}+V_{\text{at-m}}^{\parallel}+T_{\mathrm{at}}+T_{\mathrm{m}}+H_{\mathrm{F}}^{\perp}.\label{eq:H}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Atomic charges will be labelled by roman indices 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

 and the charges of the medium by greek indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu$
\end_inset

.
 The terms 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\text{at}}^{\parallel}=\frac{1}{8\pi\epsilon_{0}}\sum_{j\neq k}\frac{Q_{j}Q_{k}}{|\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\boldsymbol{r}_{k}|},\quad V_{\text{m}}^{\parallel}=\frac{1}{8\pi\epsilon_{0}}\sum_{\mu\neq\nu}\frac{Q_{\mu}Q_{\nu}}{|\boldsymbol{r}_{\mu}-\boldsymbol{r}_{\nu}|},\label{Vparallel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

represent the internal Coulomb interactions among the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 of the atomic system (placed at positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}_{k}$
\end_inset

) and among the charges 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 of the medium (placed at positions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}_{\mu}$
\end_inset

), respectively.
 The atom-medium Coulomb interactions read 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
V_{\text{at-m}}^{\parallel} & =\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\sum_{j,\mu}\frac{Q_{j}Q_{\mu}}{|\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\boldsymbol{r}_{\mu}|}.\label{eq:Vqinteract}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The kinetic terms 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mathrm{at}}=\sum_{j}\frac{\big(\bm{p}_{j}-Q_{j}\bm{A}(\boldsymbol{r}_{j})\big)^{2}}{2m_{j}},\qquad T_{\mathrm{m}}=\sum_{\mu}\frac{\big(\bm{p}_{\mu}-Q_{\mu}\bm{A}(\boldsymbol{r}_{\mu})\big)^{2}}{2m_{\mu}},\label{eq:Tminimalcoupling}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

contain the minimal coupling between the charges (with canonical momenta
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{p}_{j}=-\mathrm{i}\hbar\bm{\nabla}_{\boldsymbol{r}_{j}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{p}_{\mu}=-\mathrm{i}\hbar\bm{\nabla}_{\bm{r}_{\mu}}$
\end_inset

, and masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, respectively) and the transverse part of the field, represented by the
 Coulomb gauge vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}$
\end_inset

 (purely transverse, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\nabla}\cdot\bm{A}=0$
\end_inset

).
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\text{F}}^{\perp}=\frac{1}{2}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\left(\epsilon_{0}\dot{\boldsymbol{A}}^{2}(\boldsymbol{r})+\frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\left[\nabla\times\boldsymbol{A}(\boldsymbol{r})\right]^{2}\right)\label{eq:Hamiltonian_free_field}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the Hamiltonian of the free field in vacuum.
 If one considers a neutral atom, the charge density 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})=\sum_{j}Q_{j}\delta(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}_{j}),\quad\text{with}\quad\sum_{j}Q_{j}=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be expressed as the divergence of a polarization density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})=-\bm{\nabla}\cdot\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r}).$
\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})=\sum_{j}q_{j}\int_{0}^{1}\text{d}s\,(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})\delta(\boldsymbol{r}-\bm{R}-s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{R}$
\end_inset

 is the center-of-mass coordinate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen1_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The atomic polarization density allows us to express the Coulomb interaction
 terms as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
V_{\text{at}}^{\mathrm{\parallel}}= & \frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\text{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\left(\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{r})\right)^{2},\label{P_Coulomb}\\
V_{\text{at-m}}^{\parallel}= & \frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\text{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{r})\cdot\bm{\Pi}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{r}).\label{Pi_Coulomb}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 is the longitudinal part of the polarization, i.e.
 the only component that determines the atomic charge density, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Pi}^{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 is the longitudinal displacement field of the medium, that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\bm{\Pi}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{r})=-\sum_{\mu}Q_{\mu}\delta(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}_{\mu}).\label{eq:longitudinal_medium_displacement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The latter is proportional to the Coulomb field 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{E}^{\parallel}=-\bm{\Pi}^{\parallel}/\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 generated by the medium charges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimal coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now analyze the coupling between the atom and the electromagnetic field,
 which is a consequence of the minimal coupling in the kinetic energy terms
 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Tminimalcoupling"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For an atom modeled as a point-like dipole, it is possible to shift from
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bm{p}\cdot\bm{A}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\cdot\bm{E}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 coupling representation, through the unitary transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(-\mathrm{i}Q\boldsymbol{r}\cdot\bm{A}/\hbar)$
\end_inset

, where the vector potential is computed at the dipole center of mass
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen1_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The advantage of this transformation lies in the fact that, in the transformed
 picture, the canonical momentum of a particle coincides with its kinetic
 momentum and it is decoupled from the field variables (a thorough discussion
 of the implications of such a feature is given in Ref.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen1_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of a finite-size dipole, the aforementioned unitary transformation
 generalizes to the Power-Zienau-Wolley (PZW) operator
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen1_1997,Vogel2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{\mathrm{PZW}}=\exp\left(-\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\hbar}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})\cdot\bm{A}(\boldsymbol{r})\right)=\exp\left(-\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\hbar}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})\cdot\bm{A}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})\right).\label{eq:PZW}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The transformation property 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mathrm{PZW}}\bm{\Pi}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})U_{\mathrm{PZW}}^{\dagger}=\bm{\Pi}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})+\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})$
\end_inset

 yields two transverse-field terms from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Hamiltonian_free_field"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\mathrm{at}}^{\perp}=\frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\left(\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})\right)^{2},\qquad V_{\text{at-m}}^{\perp}=\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r})\cdot\bm{\Pi}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These contributions are complementary to the ones in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "P_Coulomb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Pi_Coulomb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The latter, as well as the transverse part of the atomic polarization density,
 are instead left unchanged by the transformation.
 Although originally 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Pi}^{\perp}=-\epsilon_{0}\bm{E}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

, the proportionality is lost after the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\Pi}(\boldsymbol{r})=-\epsilon_{0}U_{\mathrm{PZW}}\bm{E}(\boldsymbol{r})U_{\mathrm{PZW}}^{\dagger}-U_{\mathrm{PZW}}\bm{P}_{\text{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})U_{\mathrm{PZW}}^{\dagger},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be shown using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:longitudinal_medium_displacement"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a finite-size dipole, the equality between the kinetic and canonical
 momenta is not exactly realized in the transformed frame as in the case
 of a point-like dipole transformation.
 The reason is that the transformed kinetic momentum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{\mathrm{PZW}}(\bm{p}_{j}+Q_{j}\bm{A}(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}))U_{\mathrm{PZW}}^{\dagger}=\bm{p}_{j}+Q_{j}\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{d}s\,s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})\bm{B}(\bm{R}+s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R}))
\end{equation}

\end_inset

acquires an additional term, which generates a direct coupling between the
 charges and the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, the difference between the two momenta in the transformed
 representation is suppressed with respect to the analogous difference in
 the Coulomb gauge as the ratio between the atomic size and the interacting
 light wavelength.
 Therefore, if one neglects the interaction with the magnetic field, it
 can be consistently assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

–th particle kinetic momentum in the transformed representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Medium-assisted electromagnetic field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:medium"

\end_inset

 The medium-assisted electromagnetic field is an effective model that convenient
ly describes, under certain approximations, the combination of the medium
 and the field degrees of freedom, as pictured in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The contributions to the medium-assisted Hamiltonian arise from the terms
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{m}}^{\mathrm{\parallel}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{F}}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 in the Hamiltonian
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:H"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), as derived in detail in Refs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnett1996,Huttner1992,Dung2000"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The resulting effective field Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{m}}=\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\hbar\omega\bm{f}^{\dagger}(\bm{r},\omega)\cdot\bm{f}(\bm{r},\omega),\label{eq:HM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be expanded in three-component mode operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{f}(\bm{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{f}^{\dagger}(\bm{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

, satisfying canonical commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[f_{k}\left(\bm{r},\omega\right),f_{k'}^{\dagger}\left(\bm{r}',\omega'\right)\right] & =\delta_{kk'}\delta\left(\bm{r}-\bm{r}'\right)\delta\left(\omega-\omega'\right),\label{eq:CCRff1}\\
\left[f_{k}\left(\bm{r},\omega\right),f_{k'}\left(\bm{r}',\omega'\right)\right] & =\left[f_{k}^{\dagger}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right),f_{k'}^{\dagger}\left(\bm{r}',\omega'\right)\right]=0,\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The displacement field 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$
\end_inset


\series default
 and the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}$
\end_inset

 are related to the field variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{f}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{j}(\boldsymbol{r})=\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}'\Bigg[-\mathrm{i}\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\epsilon_{0}}{\pi}\epsilon_{I}(\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)}G_{jk}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)f_{k}(\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)+\mathrm{H.c.}\Bigg],\label{eq:Pij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{j}(\boldsymbol{r})=\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}'\Bigg[\frac{\omega}{c^{2}}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{\pi\epsilon_{0}}\epsilon_{I}(\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)}G_{jk}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)f_{k}(\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)+\mathrm{H.c.}\Bigg],\label{eq:Amedium}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{I}$
\end_inset

 is the imaginary part of the dielectric permittivity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)=\epsilon_{R}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)+\mathrm{i}\epsilon_{I}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have assumed that the medium is isotropic, hence the permittivity is
 a scalar.
 The Green tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 appearing in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pij"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is the solution of the equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogel2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\partial_{j}\partial_{\ell}-\delta_{j\ell}\left(\nabla^{2}+\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}\epsilon(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)\right)\right]G_{\ell k}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)=\delta_{jk}\delta(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}'),\label{eq:eqG}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the term 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Amedium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) represents its transverse part, satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial G_{\ell k}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r}',\omega)/\partial r_{\ell}=\partial G_{k\ell}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r}',\boldsymbol{r},\omega)/\partial r_{\ell}'=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the Coulomb gauge, the properties of the Green tensor and the analytic
 structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

 in the complex frequency plane guarantee that the vector potential and
 the transverse part of the displacement field satisfy the canonical commutation
 relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[A_{j}(\boldsymbol{r}),\Pi_{k}(\boldsymbol{r}')\right]=\mathrm{i}\hbar\delta_{jk}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}')=\mathrm{i}\hbar\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{q}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\left(\delta_{j\ell}-\frac{q_{j}q_{\ell}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\right)\mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}')}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a translationally invariant medium, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)=\epsilon(\omega)$
\end_inset

, thus the Green tensor depends only on the coordinate difference, 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\bm{r},\bm{r}',\omega)=G(\bm{r}-\bm{r}',\omega)$
\end_inset

, and its Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{G}_{jk}(\bm{q},\omega)=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,G_{jk}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\bm{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)= & \left(\delta_{j\ell}-\frac{q_{j}q_{\ell}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\right)\tilde{G}_{\ell k}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=\frac{\delta_{jk}-q_{j}q_{k}/|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}-\omega^{2}\epsilon(\omega)/c^{2}},\nonumber \\
\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)= & \frac{q_{j}q_{\ell}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\tilde{G}_{\ell k}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=-\frac{q_{j}q_{k}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\frac{c^{2}}{\omega^{2}\epsilon(\omega)}.\label{eq:G}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Hence, the displacement field reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{j}(\boldsymbol{r})=\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{q}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\left[-\mathrm{i}\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\epsilon_{0}}{\pi}\epsilon_{I}(\omega)}\tilde{G}_{jk}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)\tilde{f}_{k}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)\mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}}+\mathrm{H.c.}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the operators 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\bm{f}}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{f}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\bm{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\tilde{f}_{j}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega),\tilde{f}_{k}^{\dagger}(\boldsymbol{q}',\omega')]=(2\pi)^{3}\delta_{jk}\delta(\omega-\omega')\delta(\boldsymbol{q}-\boldsymbol{q}').\label{eq:CCNRf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a point-like atomic system, singularities may arise in the interaction
 Hamiltonian due to the fact that the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\parallel}(\bm{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\perp}(\bm{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

 diverge as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}\to\bm{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, while 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Im}G_{jk}^{\perp}(\bm{0},\omega)=\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{q}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\mathrm{Im}\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\perp}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=\frac{\omega^{2}\epsilon_{I}(\omega)}{c^{2}}\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{q}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\frac{\delta_{jk}-q_{j}q_{k}/|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}{\left||\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}-\frac{\omega^{2}\epsilon(\omega)}{c^{2}}\right|^{2}}\label{eq:ImGT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is finite and yields a well-defined transverse decay rate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnett1996"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Im}G^{\parallel}(\bm{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

 diverges as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}\to\bm{0}$
\end_inset

, due to the non integrability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Im}\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)\propto q_{j}q_{k}/|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}$
\end_inset

, and a consistent treatment of the longitudinal decay rate requires momentum
 regularization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Techniques based on considering the source enclosed in an artificial cavity
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key " Juzeliunas1997,Scheel1999,Barnett1999"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 have been developed to cope with such singularities.
 In the following, we will tackle the divergences of the longitudinal part
 with a less artificial approach, by considering the natural finite spatial
 extent of the atomic wavefunctions.
 This will allow us to unambiguously analyze the role of the asymmetry of
 the atomic states on the emission process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Total Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the previous parts of this section it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=H_{\mathrm{at}}+H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{el}}+H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{mag}}+H_{\mathrm{m}}.\label{eq:H_summarized}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{at}}=H_{\mathrm{at}}^{0}+V_{\mathrm{at}}=\sum_{j}\frac{\bm{p}_{j}^{2}}{2m_{j}}+\frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\left(\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the atomic Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{el}}=\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\bm{P}_{\mathrm{at}}(\boldsymbol{r})\cdot\bm{\Pi}(\boldsymbol{r})=\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\sum_{j}Q_{j}(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})\cdot\int\mathrm{d}s\,\bm{\Pi}(\bm{R}+s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R}))
\]

\end_inset

represents the interaction of the atomic system with the electric field,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{mag}}=\sum_{j} & \Bigg\{\frac{Q_{j}}{m_{j}}\bm{p}_{j}\cdot\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{d}s\,s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})\bm{B}(\bm{R}+s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R}))\nonumber \\
 & +\frac{Q_{j}^{2}}{2m_{j}}\left[\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{d}s\,s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R})\bm{B}(\bm{R}+s(\boldsymbol{r}_{j}-\bm{R}))\right]^{2}\Bigg\}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

stands for the coupling with the magnetic field.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 generally represents the Hamiltonian of the medium, that can be modeled
 in different ways, e.g.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

through the medium-assisted field Hamiltonian
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), as shown in Sect.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:medium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the following part of this work we will neglect the magnetic contribution
 to the interaction.
 We will model the atom as a dipole of charge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, with a heavy positive charge at the fixed position 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{R}=0$
\end_inset

 and a moving negative charge of coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $-\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

 and mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 As a result, one finds the final form of the interaction Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{dip}}=\frac{Q}{\epsilon_{0}}\boldsymbol{r}\cdot\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{d}s\,\bm{\Pi}(-s\boldsymbol{r}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

representing the correct generalization of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\cdot\bm{E}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Hamiltonian to an extended (non point-like) dipole.
 The expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pij"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 of the displacement field in terms of the Green tensor in the Hamiltonian
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{dip}}^{\mathrm{int}}$
\end_inset

 provides a new accurate and general approach.
 Exploiting the tensor allows one to consider different geometries of the
 host medium, in particular interfaces of different dimensions or photonic
 nanostructures, even though in the following examples we demonstrate the
 theory in the simple case of a homogeneous medium.
 However, the application of the Green's tensor leads to a divergent field
 at the position of the point-like quantum system.
 This divergence is usually removed in a somewhat artificial way by introducing
 virtual cavities or form factors.
 Here, the renormalization procedure is based on the physical size and orientati
on of the extended system represented with wavefunctions.
 It allows us to accurately describe the physics of the system without artifacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This is one of the main finding of this work, that arises as a connection
 between first-principle QED, represented through the canonical commutation
 relations, and the medium-assisted field ruled by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CCRff1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Emission properties of a bound system of charges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:emission"

\end_inset

 According to the results of the previous section, each eigenstate of the
 internal atomic Hamiltonian is dressed by the surrounding medium.
 We now characterize the single-photon emission process and the Lamb shift
 of an atomic level in a medium-assisted photonic environment in a translational
ly invariant medium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an atom in an arbitrary environment, i.e.
 a dispersive medium of any geometry and material.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 be two orthogonal eigenstates of the free atomic Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{at}}$
\end_inset

, characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{at}}\left|a\right\rangle =E_{a}\left|a\right\rangle ,\quad H_{\mathrm{at}}\left|b\right\rangle =E_{b}\left|b\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The atom-photon interaction is described by the matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{j}^{ab}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)=\left\langle a\right|H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{dip}}f_{j}^{\dagger}(\boldsymbol{r},\omega)\left|b\right\rangle ,\label{matrixM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which, for a translationally-invariant medium, can be expressed in the Fourier
 space through 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_{j}^{ab}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=\left\langle a\right|H_{\mathrm{int}}^{\mathrm{dip}}\tilde{f}_{j}^{\dagger}(\bm{q},\omega)\left|b\right\rangle =-\mathrm{i}C(\omega)\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}%\sum_{k=1,2,3}
\tilde{G}_{jk}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)\left\langle a\right|r_{k}\int_{0}^{1}ds\;\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}s\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}}\left|b\right\rangle ,\label{eq:M}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C(\omega)=Q\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\epsilon_{I}(\omega)}{8\pi^{4}\epsilon_{0}}}.
\]

\end_inset

If we insert the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{G}_{jk}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:G"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and exploit the orthogonality between longitudinal and transverse projectors,
 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{T}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega) & = & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left|\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_{j}^{ab}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)\right|^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{C(\omega)^{2}}{|\epsilon(\omega)|^{2}}\Biggl[\mathcal{D}(|\boldsymbol{q}|,\omega)\mathcal{G}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q})+(1-\mathcal{D}(|\boldsymbol{q}|,\omega))\frac{|\mathcal{F}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q})-\delta_{ab}|^{2}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\Biggr],\label{eq:T}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ab}=\langle a|b\rangle=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 coincide and 0 otherwise, with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{D}(q,\omega) & =\left|1-\frac{q^{2}c^{2}}{\omega^{2}\epsilon(\omega)}\right|^{-2},\\
\mathcal{F}_{ab}(\bm{q}) & =\left\langle a\right|\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}}\left|b\right\rangle =\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{r}\,\psi_{a}^{*}(\boldsymbol{r})\psi_{b}(\boldsymbol{r})\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}},\\
\mathcal{G}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q}) & =\sum_{j=1}^{3}\left|\left\langle a\right|r_{j}\frac{\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}}-1}{\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}}\left|b\right\rangle \right|^{2}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Notice that the longitudinal contribution is cancelled by part of the transvers
e one in the limit $
\backslash
to0$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

The quantity defined in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:T"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) determines both the total decay rate of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and its energy shift.
 The former can be evaluated according to the Fermi golden rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Gamma_{a}= & \frac{2\pi}{\hbar}\sum_{b}\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\delta(\hbar\omega-\hbar\omega_{ab})T_{ab}(\omega)=\frac{2\pi}{\hbar^{2}}\sum_{b\neq a}\theta(\omega_{ab})T_{ab}(\omega_{ab}),\label{eq:Gamma-1}\\
= & \frac{2\pi}{\hbar}\sum_{b\neq a}\theta\left(\omega_{ab}\right)\frac{C\left(\omega_{ab}\right)^{2}}{\left|\epsilon\left(\omega_{ab}\right)\right|^{2}}\int\left[\mathcal{D}\left(|\boldsymbol{q}|,\omega_{ab}\right)\mathcal{G}_{ab}\left(\boldsymbol{q}\right)+\left(1-\mathcal{D}\left(|\boldsymbol{q}|,\omega\right)\right)\frac{|\mathcal{F}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q})|^{2}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\right]\mathrm{d^{2}}\boldsymbol{q}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{ab}=\frac{E_{a}-E_{b}}{\hbar},\qquad T_{ab}(\omega)=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{q}\,\mathcal{T}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega),\label{eq:Tab}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(x)$
\end_inset

 being the Heaviside step function.
 The absence of a contribution from state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 in the sum over states in the second equality of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gamma-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), albeit reasonable, is not a trivial result.
 Therefore, replacing Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:T"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

in the evaluation of the decay rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ab}=0$
\end_inset

 and the apparent divergence in the term proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 is regularized by the wavefunctions spatial extension.
 Note that the two terms in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gamma-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\left(\boldsymbol{q},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 correspond to the transverse contribution, while the remaining one is the
 longitudinal contribution responsible for non-radiative decay, because
 it is related to the absorption losses in the dielectric host medium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In vacuum (
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(\omega)=1$
\end_inset

), the decay rate in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gamma-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{a}^{\mathrm{(vac)}}=\frac{Q^{2}q^{3}}{8\pi^{2}\hbar\epsilon_{0}}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}\mathrm{d}^{2}S(\bm{n})\sum_{b\neq a}\Big[\mathcal{G}_{ab}(q\bm{n})-\frac{|\mathcal{F}_{ab}(q\bm{n})|^{2}}{q^{2}}\Big],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\omega_{ab}/c$
\end_inset

 and the integration is over the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{n}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that in the point-dipole limit the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way, we recover the familiar Weisskopf-Wigner result
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cohen2_1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The frequency shifts of the atomic levels should be determined using Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:T"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Tab"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), through 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{a}=\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\sum_{b}\mathrm{P}\!\!\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\frac{T_{ab}(\omega)}{\omega-\omega_{ab}},\label{eq:delta_a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}\!\!\int$
\end_inset

 denoting principal value integration.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 contains the state-independent, non-integrable term 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{ab}C(\omega)^{2}|\boldsymbol{q}|^{-2}(1-\mathcal{D}(|\boldsymbol{q}|,\omega))\sim|\boldsymbol{q}|^{-2}\quad\text{as }|\boldsymbol{q}|\to\infty,\label{eq:nonint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which provides a divergent contribution to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{aa}(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 However, this contribution is also independent of the state, representing
 therefore the effect of a uniform energy shift.
 Physical quantities such as the perturbed transition frequency 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{\omega}_{ab}=\omega_{ab}+\Delta_{a}-\Delta_{b} & =\omega_{ab}+\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\mathrm{P}\!\!\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}\omega\Biggl[\frac{T_{aa}(\omega)-T_{bb}(\omega)}{\omega}\nonumber \\
 & +2\omega_{ab}\frac{T_{ab}(\omega)}{\omega^{2}-\omega_{ab}^{2}}+\sum_{c\neq a,b}\left(\frac{T_{ac}(\omega)}{\omega-\omega_{ac}}-\frac{T_{bc}(\omega)}{\omega-\omega_{bc}}\right)\Biggr]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

are thus independent of the divergent term given in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Indeed, notice that, in the time domain the low-energy behavior of the
 dielectric permittivity is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(\omega)=1+\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}t\chi(t)+\mathrm{i}\omega\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}t\,t\chi(t)+O(\omega^{2}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(t)$
\end_inset

 is the medium susceptibility with finite moments.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}(\omega)\sim\omega$
\end_inset

 close to the origin, and therefore the integration of the term 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{aa}-T_{bb})/\omega$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:omega_ab"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is well defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Asymmetric two-level atom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parity asymmetry of the atomic Hamiltonian eigenstates, reflected by
 the presence of nonvanishing expectation values of one or more components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

, affects the state-dependent quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{ab}$
\end_inset

, which appear in the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 and determine the decay rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{a}$
\end_inset

 and the energy shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In a two-level atomic system, the three components of the Hermitian position
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{r}$
\end_inset

 can be represented by spin operators
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "feynman1964,cohen2_1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{r}=\bm{\rho}\bm{1}+\bm{\delta}\sigma_{z}+\bm{r}_{ab}\sigma_{x},\qquad\sigma_{x}=\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle b\right|+\left|b\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|,\quad\sigma_{z}=\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|-\left|b\right\rangle \left\langle b\right|\label{eq:rspin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

acting on the two-dimensional space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle ,\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\bm{\rho} & =\frac{\left\langle a\right|\bm{r}\left|a\right\rangle +\left\langle b\right|\bm{r}\left|b\right\rangle }{2},\label{eq:rho}\\
\bm{\delta} & =\frac{\left\langle a\right|\bm{r}\left|a\right\rangle -\left\langle b\right|\bm{r}\left|b\right\rangle }{2},\\
\bm{r}_{ab} & =\left\langle a\right|\bm{r}\left|b\right\rangle =\left\langle b\right|\bm{r}\left|a\right\rangle .\label{eq:rab}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

In the two-level case, the off-diagonal matrix element
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rab"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be made real and non-negative by absorbing a phase factor in the definitio
n of one of the states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The functions that determine the decay rate from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 read 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{F}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q}) & =-\mathrm{i}\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\rho}}\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab}\,\mathrm{sinc}(A(\boldsymbol{q})),\label{eq:Fab}\\
\mathcal{G}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q}) & =\left|\nabla_{\bm{q}}\left[\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab}\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{sinc}(sA(\boldsymbol{q}))\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}s\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\rho}}\mathrm{d}s\right]\right|^{2},\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{sinc}(x)=\sin(x)/x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\boldsymbol{q})=\sqrt{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})^{2}+(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\delta})^{2}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
From these results, one can observe that the physical quantities computed
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 and from the square modulus of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 are invariant with respect to the inversions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\rho}\to-\bm{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\delta}\to\bm{-\delta}$
\end_inset

, but both depend on diagonal entries and which play the role of the asymmetric
 contributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
To identify the lowest-order contributions to the decay rate, let us perform
 a small-
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset

 expansion of the functions appearing in the expression
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:T"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{ab}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{|\mathcal{F}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q})|^{2}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\simeq\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})^{2}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\!\left(1-\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})^{2}+(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\delta})^{2}}{6}\right)\!,\label{eq:Fabappr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{G}_{ab}(\boldsymbol{q})\simeq & |\boldsymbol{r}_{ab}|^{2}\!\left(1-\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})^{2}}{3}+\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\delta})^{2}}{9}+\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\rho})^{2}}{12}\right)\nonumber \\
+ & \frac{|\bm{\rho}|^{2}(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})^{2}}{4}+(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}_{ab})\boldsymbol{r}_{ab}\cdot\left(\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\rho})\bm{\rho}}{2}-\frac{(\boldsymbol{q}\cdot\bm{\delta})\bm{\delta}}{9}\right).\label{eq:Gabappr}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

While the first-order contributions are regular, the second-order approximation
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset

 of the functions in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fabappr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gabappr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) yield divergent integrals, that should be regularized by a cutoff 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\boldsymbol{q}}$
\end_inset

, roughly corresponding to the inverse spatial size of the involved wavefunction
s, that can range from 1 to 100 nm according to the considered system.
 Clearly, this cutoff is not needed if one uses the expressions in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fab"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), that contains all orders in q.
 Based on the approximations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fabappr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gabappr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 one can estimate that the corrections entailed by an asymmetry of the states
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are of order 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Lambda_{\boldsymbol{q}}|\boldsymbol{r}_{aa}|)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Lambda_{\boldsymbol{q}}|\boldsymbol{r}_{bb}|)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the asymmetry corrections compete with terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Lambda_{\bm{q}}|\bm{r}_{ab}|)^{2}$
\end_inset

, representing the first corrections to the point-dipole result, and are
 not characterized by a definite sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We have expressed a light-matter interaction Hamiltonian in terms of the
 Green tensor propagator, in a novel approach that avoids the usual divergence
 related to the approximation of a point-like atomic quantum system.
 The divergence was lifted via the inclusion of the wavefunctions, providing
 in this way a natural cutoff for the system investigated.
 The analysis focused on the determination of the decay rates and energy
 shifts of the bound states of an 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

atomic
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 system, which have been obtained under general assumptions.
 The most important among these assumptions is the hypothesis of homogeneous
 and isotropic media.
 We also discussed how to extend the theory to more general situations.
 In [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ScalaNJP2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

] the general result obtained are applied to the decay rate as a function
 of the asymmetry of the system and the absorption of the medium showing
 that asymmetry can yield small but detectable deviations with respect to
 the symmetric case.
 In the next section we introduce the effect of the asymmetry in the Rabi
 model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Beyond the Rabi model: light interactions with polar atomic systems in a
 cavity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In quantum optics, the Rabi model accounts for a coupling of a single electromag
netic mode with a two-level atomic system characterized with inversion symmetry.
 The coupling occurs via two types of terms.
 The usually dominant resonant terms describe energy exchange between photonic
 and atomic excitations.
 The so-called counter-rotating terms are typically much weaker.
 They account for a simultaneous emission or absorption of a pair of excitations
, one in the atomic system and one in the electromagnetic mode.
 In the electric-dipole approximation, these interaction terms arise from
 the coupling of the electric field with an 
\emph on
induced
\emph default
 transition dipole moment.
 If the inversion symmetry of the atomic system is broken, it becomes polar,
 which means that its eigenstates may acquire 
\emph on
permanent
\emph default
 electric dipole moments.
 As a consequence, a third type of terms describing light-matter interaction
 arises, related to the coupling of the permanent dipoles to the electric
 field.
 In this work, based on the time-independent perturbation theory, we compare
 light emission intensities induced by the three types of terms.
 The analysis reveals that the emission strength related to the existence
 of permanent dipoles may surpass the one due to the counter-rotating interactio
n terms, but usually is much weaker than the emission due to the main, resonant
 coupling.
 This ratio can be modified in systems with a reduced dimensionality or
 through engineering of the density of electromagnetic states of the environment
, as we demonstrate with a Lorentzian example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rabi model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Rabi model is the fundamental model in quantum optics, which describes
 the coupling of a two-level system and a bosonic field mode 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Xie2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The model extends beyond the simpler Jaynes-Cummings interaction, in which
 the energy is exchanged between the atomic excitation and a photon, such
 that creation of a photon is accompanied by annihilation of the atomic
 excitation and vice versa
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shore1993"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The Rabi model additionally accounts for the less intuitive processes of
 pairwise creation or annihilation of excitations in the atomic and photonic
 subsystems.
 The probability of these processes grows with the light-matter coupling
 constant and becomes significant in the so-called ultrastrong coupling
 regime, in which that coupling constant becomes comparable to the energy
 of the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FornDiaz2019"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Numerous experimental realizations include superconducting systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bourassa2009,Niemczyk2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 quantum wells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gunter2009,Zhang2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, photonic waveguide arrays 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Crespi2012PLR"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, molecular ensembles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "George2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, cold atoms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schneeweiss2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, etc.
 In all these systems extension beyond the Jaynes-Cummings interaction may
 lead to considerable modification of the physics of the system: in particular,
 to a ground state with a nonvanishing number of excitations, squeezing
 dynamic, and a significant modification of the spectra 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Braak2011,Chen2012,Xie2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Remarkably, analytical solutions of the Rabi model have been developed
 only in the last decade 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Braak2011,Chen2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hex.pdf
	width 80text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Artistic vision of the system under study: a two-level spatially asymmetric
 atomic system in a lossy cavity.
 The annihilation and creation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 for the lossy cavity system, and analogously the annihilation and creation
 operators 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 for the reservoir.
 The decay rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 of the cavity system is ruled by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "key-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Hex"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The Rabi model describes the light - matter interaction scenario, where
 electromagnetic field induces transitions between the eigenstates of the
 two-level atomic system.
 A particular mechanism is related to a coupling of the electromagnetic
 radiation with a transition dipole moment element induced between a pair
 of atomic eigenstates.
 However, simple two-level systems may sustain much richer physics, beyond
 the traditional Rabi model: a particular example is a coupling scenario
 where the electromagnetic field introduces energy shifts of the eigenstates
 rather than transitions between them 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kibis_asymm_semiclass,Paspalakis2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A simple realization exploits atomic systems with permanent dipole moments
 e.g.
 polar molecules or asymmetric quantum dots.
 Due to the interplay of permanent and induced electric dipole moments,
 polar systems are a playground where rich physics of light-matter interactions
 can be realized: polar quantum systems have been proposed for THz radiation
 sources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kibis_asymm_semiclass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 based on quantum dots 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chestnov2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 or molecular ensembles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gladysz2020a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 They can be exploited for squeezed light generation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "koppenhofer2016,Anton2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and they support nonlinear optical absorption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Paspalakis2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, the impact of spatial asymmetry of a quantum system on its spontaneou
s emission properties has been investigated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ScalaNJP2020"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Said works just sketch the plethora of possibilities provided by asymmetric
 quantum systems that simultaneously support light-matter interactions through
 three mechanisms.
 These correspond to the Jaynes - Cummings terms and the counter - rotating
 terms, both involving the transition dipole moments of the atomic system,
 and the scenario based on its permanent dipoles.
 For numerous applications given above it is essential to identify conditions
 in terms of experimentally tunable model parameters where different contributio
ns make a significant influence on the system's optical response.
 This is our goal in this work.
 We study the relative impact of the three contributions and demonstrate
 with simple examples the possibility to tune it with density-of-states
 engineering.
 Our analysis follows the methodology introduced in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savenko2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but extends it to include all the three interaction mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hamiltonian of the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider a two level system with a ground and excited state denoted
 respectively as 
\begin_inset Formula $|g\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|e\rangle$
\end_inset

, separated with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The system is described by a set of Pauli operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{-}=|g\rangle\langle e|$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{+}=|e\rangle\langle g|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}=|e\rangle\langle e|-|g\rangle\langle g|$
\end_inset

.
 The two-level system interacts with a single electromagnetic mode with
 an annihilation operator 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 The Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of the coupled system can be divided in two parts 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{int}}=H_{\mathrm{JC}}+V.\label{key-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first term is the Jaynes-Cumming (JC) Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shore1993"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{JC}}=\hbar\omega_{c}a^{\dagger}a+\hbar\frac{\omega_{a}}{2}\sigma_{z}+\hbar g_{R}(\sigma_{+}a+a^{\dagger}\sigma_{-})\label{eq:HJC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 is the coupling strength between the parties of the system through the
 resonant JC channel.
 The following analysis could be performed without specification of the
 coupling mechanism.
 However, we will interpret the model for the physically important case
 of electric-dipole coupling in a rectangular cavity, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}=-\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{eg}}\cdot\bm{\epsilon}\sqrt{\hbar\omega_{c}/2\epsilon_{0}\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{eg}}=-\langle e|\boldsymbol{d}|g\rangle$
\end_inset

 stands for the off-diagonal element of the electric dipole operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}$
\end_inset

 of the two-level system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the polarization versor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 denotes vacuum electric permittivity and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is the quantization volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "key-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 accounts for the interaction of the two-level system and the electromagnetic
 mode through the counter-rotating (CR) mechanism and the diagonal-dipole
 mechanism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V & =H_{\mathrm{CR}}+H_{\mathrm{diag}},\label{eq:HS_HR}\\
H_{\mathrm{CR}}=\hbar g_{R}\left(\sigma_{+}a^{\dagger}+\sigma_{-}a\right), & \qquad H_{\mathrm{AS}}=\hbar g_{S}\left(\sigma_{z}+\boldsymbol{1}\right)\left(a+a^{\dagger}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}=-\bm{d}_{\mathrm{ee}}\cdot\bm{\epsilon}\sqrt{\hbar\omega_{c}/8\epsilon_{0}\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

, proportional to the diagonal element of the dipole moment operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Note that the expectation value of a dipole moment operator described only
 by off-diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{eg}}|e\rangle\langle g|+\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{eg}}^{*}|g\rangle\langle e|$
\end_inset

 may be nonzero only at presence of transitions between the eigenstates
 that may be induced with external electric field.
 Therefore, these elements correspond to induced transition dipoles.
 Contrary, the diagonal element describes the permanent dipole moment of
 the excited state.
 Here, we have assumed for simplicity that the ground state does not sustain
 a dipole moment: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{gg}}\right|=0$
\end_inset

, but the analysis can be generalized in a straightforward manner to include
 this quantity and will not lead to qualitatively new effects.
 Notably, permanent dipole moments are sustained by polar systems, i.e.
 systems without inversion symmetry 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kibis_asymm_semiclass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For this reason we will refer to the last Hamiltonian term as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asymmetry term
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and mark it with the AS subscript.
 Finally, note that while the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{JC}}$
\end_inset

 preserves the number of excitations, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{AS}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

) describes a modification of this number by 1 (by 2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Perturbative analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following analysis we will treat 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as a perturbation with respect to the system Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{JC}}$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{JC}}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{n}^{s(0)}=\hbar\omega_{c}\left(n-\frac{1}{2}\right)+s\hbar\sqrt{\frac{\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{a}\right)^{2}}{4}+ng_{R}^{2}}\label{energieslevel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\pm1$
\end_inset

, and the eigenstates are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|n_{s}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle =A_{n}^{s}\left|g;n\right\rangle +B_{n}^{s}\left|e,n-1\right\rangle ,\label{eq:psi0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A_{n}^{s} & =\frac{E_{n}^{s(0)}-\hbar\omega_{c}\left(n-1\right)-\hbar\omega_{a}/2}{\sqrt{\Bigl(E_{n}^{s(0)}-\hbar\omega_{c}(n-1)-\hbar\omega_{a}/2\Bigr)^{2}+\hbar^{2}g_{R}^{2}n}},\\
B_{n}^{s} & =\frac{\hbar g_{r}\sqrt{n}}{\sqrt{\Bigl(E_{n}^{s(0)}-\hbar\omega_{c}(n-1)-\hbar\omega_{a}/2\Bigr)^{2}+\hbar^{2}g_{R}^{2}n}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|n_{s}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle \right\} _{s=\pm}$
\end_inset

 defines a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{JC}}\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

, which is the set of the states with the same number of the excitations
 (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 We denote it with the JC subscript, since the notion of the manifold will
 be generalized in the perturbed picture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In the perturbation Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, the counter-rotating term 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

 is described by the same coupling constant 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 as the interaction term of the unperturbed Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{JC}}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the transition rates due to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

 are much smaller since we assume to work far from the ultra-strong coupling
 regime 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}\ll\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the perturbation theory approach is justified for up to moderate
 coupling strengths, as we show later on.
 We characterize the modified eigenstates with the time-independent perturbation
 theory up to the second order, with the wavefunction expansion given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n_{s}\right\rangle =\left|n_{s}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle +\left|n_{s}^{\left(1\right)}\right\rangle +\left|n_{s}^{\left(2\right)}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The first-order correction reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|n_{s}^{\left(1\right)}\right\rangle =\sum_{m\neq n}\sum_{\alpha=\pm}\frac{V_{mn}^{\alpha s}}{E_{nm}^{s\alpha}}\left|m_{\alpha}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle \equiv\frac{V_{mn}^{\alpha s}}{E_{nm}^{s\alpha}}\left|m_{\alpha}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle ,\label{def:first_order_state}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n,m}^{s,\alpha}=E_{n}^{s\left(0\right)}-E_{m}^{\alpha\left(0\right)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{mn}^{\alpha s}=\left\langle m_{\alpha}^{\left(0\right)}|V|n_{s}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V_{mn}^{\alpha s}= & \hbar g_{R}\Bigg(\sqrt{n-1}B_{n}^{s}A_{n-2}^{\alpha}\delta_{m,n-2}+\sqrt{n+1}A_{n}^{s}B_{n+2}^{\alpha}\delta_{m,n+2}\Bigg)\nonumber \\
+ & 2\hbar g_{S}B_{m}^{\alpha}B_{n}^{s}\left(\sqrt{n-1}\delta_{m,n-1}+\sqrt{n}\delta_{m,n+1}\right).\label{eq:Vmn}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The above equation shows that the perturbed eigenstates include admixtures
 of states with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n\pm1$
\end_inset

 coupled by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

 and of states with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n\pm2$
\end_inset

 coupled by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

, which follows directly from the forms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{diag}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

 Hamiltonians.
 Including the second-order correction leads to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|n_{s}\right\rangle =\left(1-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k}\sum_{\alpha=\pm}\left(\frac{V_{nk}^{s\alpha}}{\varepsilon_{nk}^{s\alpha}}\right)^{2}\right)\left|n_{s}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle +\sum_{k}\sum_{\alpha=\pm}\left(\frac{V_{kn}^{\alpha s}}{\varepsilon_{nk}^{s\alpha}}+\sum_{l}\sum_{\beta=\pm}\frac{V_{kl}^{\alpha\beta}V_{ln}^{\beta s}}{\varepsilon_{nk}^{s\alpha}\varepsilon_{nl}^{s\beta}}\right)\left|k_{\alpha}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle .\label{eq:ket_2nd_order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Based on the above result, we define generalized manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 as the pairs
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|n_{s}\right\rangle \right\} _{s=\pm}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the 2nd order perturbation, the eigenstate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n_{s}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 includes superposition components with different numbers of excitations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ n,n\pm1,\dots,n\pm4\right\} $
\end_inset

, while the label 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 refers to the central component, which is by far the leading superposition
 component for weak enough coupling strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R,S}$
\end_inset

, for which the theory is applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The correction 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 does not perturb the eigenvalues at the first order, because 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{nn}}^{s\sigma}=\left\langle n_{s}|V|n_{\sigma}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

.
 Up to the second order, the energy eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}^{s}=E_{n}^{s\left(0\right)}+E_{n}^{s\left(1\right)}+E_{n}^{s\left(2\right)}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}^{s\left(1\right)}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{n}^{s\left(2\right)}=\sum_{k\neq n}\sum_{j=\pm}\frac{\left(V_{kn}^{js}\right)^{2}}{E_{nk}^{sj}}.\label{eq:energy_2nd_order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inclusion of the second-order corrections provides us with a method to estimate
 the range of validity for the theory, as described related section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Outcoupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we assume the cavity mirrors to be semi-transparent, so
 that the cavity photons described by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 may exchange energy with an external reservoir mode 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 at a rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 This approach follows directly the reasoning in Ref.~
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savenko2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{ex}}=\hbar\Gamma(ar^{\dagger}+a^{\dagger}r).\label{key-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This Hamiltonian effectively models losses, since we assume the reservoir
 mode to be in the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The Fermi golden rule allows us to find the emission spectrum into the reservoir
 mode, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
S\left(\omega\right)=\sum_{\iota,\phi=\pm}\sum_{i_{\iota},f_{\phi}} & \left|\left\langle f_{\phi},1_{R}|H_{\mathrm{ex}}|i_{\iota},0_{R}\right\rangle \right|^{2}L_{\mathrm{fi}}\left(\omega\right)\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right),\label{eq:spec}\\
L_{\mathrm{fi}}(\omega)=\frac{1}{2\pi} & \frac{\hbar\gamma}{(E_{\mathrm{if}}^{\iota\phi}-\hbar\omega)^{2}+\left(\frac{\hbar\gamma}{2}\right)^{2}}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We include contributions from all 
\begin_inset Formula $|i_{\iota}\rangle\rightarrow|f_{\phi}\rangle$
\end_inset

 transitions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|i_{\iota}\rangle,|f_{\phi}\rangle\in\left\{ \left|n_{s}\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}^{\iota(0)}>E_{f}^{\phi(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 To evaluate the contribution from a given pair of states, the corresponding
 transition element 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle f_{\phi},1_{R}|H_{\mathrm{ex}}|i_{\iota},0_{R}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 must be weighted with the Lorentzian distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathrm{fi}}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 which accounts for the emission linewidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 due to the finite lifetime of the cavity photons.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{if}^{\iota\phi}=E_{i}^{\iota}-E_{f}^{\phi}$
\end_inset


\color blue
 
\color inherit
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 stands for the density of reservoir states.
 Since we fix the initial and final states of the reservoir, we can simplify
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\left\langle f_{\phi},1_{R}|H_{\mathrm{ex}}|i_{\iota},0_{R}\right\rangle \right|^{2}\sim\left|\left\langle f_{\phi}|a|i_{\iota}\right\rangle \right|^{2}=\left|a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}\right|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 as the relevant quantity that contributes to the emission rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We now define a transition rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}$
\end_inset

 that accounts for the emission through a given transition in a certain
 spectral range 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega$
\end_inset

, which covers the emission bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{f,i}^{\phi\iota} & =\frac{2\pi}{\hbar}\int_{\delta\omega}\left|\left\langle f_{\phi},1_{R}|H_{\mathrm{ex}}|i_{\iota},0_{R}\right\rangle \right|^{2}L_{fi}\left(\omega\right)\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right)d\omega.\label{eq:intensity-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Next, we assume the density of states which corresponds to a free space
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(\omega\right)=\left(\frac{L}{\pi c}\right)^{p+1}\omega^{p}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the quantization length and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0,1,2$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian exponent related to the dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d=p+1$
\end_inset

 of the system.
 For a sufficiently narrow transition 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\ll\omega$
\end_inset

, which can be safely assumed for a great majority of systems, the density
 of states can be approximated as a constant value across the transition
 bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(\omega)\sim\left(\hbar\omega\right)^{p}\approx\left(E_{if}^{\iota\phi}\right)^{p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{f,i}^{\phi\iota} & \propto\int_{\delta\omega}\left|a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}\right|^{2}L_{fi}\left(\omega\right)\left(\hbar\omega\right)^{p}\mathrm{d}\omega\approx\left|a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}\right|^{2}\left(E_{if}^{\iota\phi}\right)^{p}.\label{eq:Pofp-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We now evaluate the transition amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 At the 
\begin_inset Formula $0-$
\end_inset

th order, we find directly from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:psi0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle f_{\phi}^{\left(0\right)}|a|i_{\iota}^{\left(0\right)}\right\rangle \equiv & c_{i}^{\phi\iota}\delta_{f,i-1}=\left(\sqrt{i}A_{i}^{\iota}A_{i-1}^{\phi}+\sqrt{i-1}B_{i}^{\iota}B_{i-1}^{\phi}\right)\delta_{f,i-1}.\label{eq:Frl}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This equation shows that only transitions between two subsequent excitation
 manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E_{\mathrm{JC}}}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{JC}}\left(i-1\right)$
\end_inset

 are allowed in the Jaynes-Cummings model, as expected.
 Our goal is to analyze the emission probability via Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intensity-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 when the eigenstates are corrected by the perturbation term 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HS_HR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and the spectrum is defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "energieslevel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 In the perturbed expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{f,i}^{\phi\iota}=\left\langle f_{\phi}|a|i_{\iota}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, that is in the eigenstates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n_{s}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, we consider all the correction terms up to the second order in the coupling
 strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\color black
Using 
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{nn}}=0$
\end_inset

, we find 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left|\left\langle f_{\phi}|a|i_{\iota}\right\rangle \right|^{2}=\left|\frac{V_{f+1,i}^{\alpha\iota}}{\varepsilon_{i,f+1}^{\iota\alpha}}c_{f+1}^{\phi\alpha}+\frac{V_{i+1,f}^{\alpha\phi}}{\varepsilon_{f,i+1}^{\phi\alpha}}c_{i}^{\alpha\iota}\right|^{2}+\delta_{f,i-1}\Bigg\{\left(1-\left(\frac{V_{ik}^{\iota\alpha}}{\varepsilon_{ik}^{\iota\alpha}}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{V_{fk}^{\phi\alpha}}{\varepsilon_{fk}^{\phi\alpha}}\right)^{2}\right)\left|c_{i}^{\phi\iota}\right|^{2}\nonumber \\
+2c_{i}^{\phi\iota}\left(\frac{V_{il}^{\alpha\beta}V_{li}^{\beta\iota}}{\varepsilon_{ii}^{\iota\alpha}\varepsilon_{il}^{\iota\beta}}c_{i}^{\phi\alpha}+\frac{V_{k-1,i-1}^{\alpha\phi}}{\varepsilon_{i-1,k-1}^{\phi\alpha}}\frac{V_{ki}^{\alpha'\iota}}{\varepsilon_{ik}^{\iota\alpha'}}c_{k}^{\alpha\alpha'}+\frac{V_{i-1,l}^{\alpha\beta}V_{l,i-1}^{\beta\phi}}{\varepsilon_{i-1,i-1}^{\phi\alpha}\varepsilon_{i-1,l}^{\phi\beta}}c_{i}^{\alpha\iota}\right)\bigg\}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Inclusion of the perturbation Hamiltonian allows transitions to new manifolds.
 A close inspection of the form the perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Vmn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) combined with the above form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle f_{\phi}|a|i_{\iota}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 reveals that transitions between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(i\right)\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}\left(f=i\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(i\right)\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}\left(f=i-2\right)$
\end_inset

 are due to the asymmetric Hamiltonian
\color blue
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{AS}}$
\end_inset


\color inherit
 and the transition between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(i\right)\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}\left(i-3\right)$
\end_inset

 are due to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

.
 The latter would also give rise to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(i\right)\longrightarrow\mathcal{E}\left(i+1\right)$
\end_inset

 transitions, which are suppressed in a vacuum reservoir mode 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 One might argue that this fact suggests a stronger contribution comes from
 the diagonal coupling than the counter-rotating terms because the former
 involves closer manifolds, hence is energetically more favorite.
 On the other hand, the transitions at higher frequencies contribute with
 an higher intensity due to the increased density of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we need a quantitative comparison which evaluates the spectrum
 and highlights properly the behavior in different regimes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we analyze the transitions showed in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, with a special emphasis on the ones induced by the perturbation Hamiltonian
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{AS}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\mathrm{CR}}$
\end_inset

.
 We will investigate relative emission strengths of transitions that origin
 from different Hamiltonian contributions in function of the coupling constants
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R,S}$
\end_inset

.
 We also estimate the range of applicability of the theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

