name "fig:energy_10_resonance"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition frequencies will naturally depend on the coupling strength
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

, as already follows from the Jaynes-Cummings theory, and weakly on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

 through the second order perturbation [Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:energy_2nd_order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)].
 The Jaynes-Cummings energy structure is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:energy_10_resonance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the states from 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $n=10$
\end_inset

 manifolds, both in a resonant 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}=\omega_{a}$
\end_inset

 and detuned case 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}-\omega_{a}=0.2\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In the 
\color red
A
\color inherit
ppendix, we argue that the range of applicability of the theory is limited
 by the first crossing of the states with energies below the initial state,
 which sets an upper limit on the coupling strength 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 An even stronger limit is imposed by a normalization condition for the
 eigenstates (see the Appendix).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename spectrum.eps
	width 48text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename spectrum0.eps
	width 48text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Emission spectra (arbitrary units) from the initial states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{+}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (blue) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{-}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (orange) for the three- (a) and one-dimentional space (b), respectively
 sustaining densities of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{p}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 (a) and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 (b).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:spec"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the emission spectrum includes a set of approximately Lorentzian peaks.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we separately plot spectra for the initial states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{+}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (solid blue line) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{-}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (dashed orange line), for the resonant case 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{a}=\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 and fixed coupling strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}=g_{S}=0.1\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 The spectra are plotted for two different densities of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\sim\omega^{2}$
\end_inset

 [Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(a)] and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P=\mathrm{const.}}$
\end_inset

 [Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(b)].
 The single low-energy peak around 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2\sqrt{10}g_{R}\approx0.63\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{+}\right\rangle \rightarrow\left|10_{-}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 transition induced by the inversion-symmetry breaking of the two-level
 system and might unveil applications for low-frequency-sources.
 Therefore, its tunability is an important feature: the position of this
 peak depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 on the system's permanent dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{d}_{\mathrm{ee}}$
\end_inset

 and on the field strength in the cavity related to the number of photons.
 In the classical limit, this provides the tuning possibility with the field
 amplitude 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kibis_asymm_semiclass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, tuning could be achieved through orientation of the permanent
 dipole moment of the two-level system with an external DC electric field
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gladysz2020a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Around 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 we recognize the Mollow triplet that arises from the JC interaction.
 Similar structures are repeated around 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=2\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=3\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

, arising respectively from the AS and CR Hamiltonian perturbations.
 Note that the positions of sidebands of the Mollow-like triplet around
 
\begin_inset Formula $2\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 are related to the diagonal dipole moment and will accordingly be modified
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

 is tuned.
 We emphasize that all the peaks including the Mollow-like sidebands can
 be resolved in the spectra.
 In particular, even though the low-energy peak usually corresponds to the
 weakest transition intensities, it appears on top of a correspondingly
 suppressed background.
 In consequence, the signal-to-noise ratio is found comparable for all emission
 peaks.
 Below we analyze the intensity ratio of different peaks depending on the
 coupling strengths of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We study three selected transitions representative for each Hamiltonian
 contribution, highlighted as thick arrows in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: for the Jaynes-Cummings term we select the 
\begin_inset Formula $|10_{+}\rangle\rightarrow|9_{+}\rangle$
\end_inset

 transition, for the diagonal coupling term - the 
\begin_inset Formula $|10_{+}\rangle\rightarrow|10_{-}\rangle$
\end_inset

 transition, for the counter-rotating term - the 
\begin_inset Formula $|10_{+}\rangle\rightarrow|7_{-}\rangle$
\end_inset

 transition that corresponds to the highest frequency.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(a), we plot the squared amplitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle f_{\phi}|a|i_{\iota}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 which determine the transition probability in the one-dimentional case
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 [Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pofp-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)].
 The squared ampitudes are plotted separately for each of the considered
 transitions.
 As anticipated, the contribution due to the Jaynes-Cummings interaction
 is the leading term, overcoming other terms by several orders of magnitude
 for the investigated range of the coupling strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The JC contribution itself weakly depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

, though, which is also expected: the set of perturbed eigenstates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ |n_{\pm}\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

 which are used as a basis closely corresponds to the Jaynes-Cummings basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ |n_{\pm}^{(0)}\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

, from which it weakly deviates for large 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The purple (red) lines in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 correspond to squared amplitudes for the selected transitions induced by
 the AS (CR) Hamiltonian, respectively.
 Results obtained for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}=g_{R},\:\frac{g_{R}}{10},\:\frac{g_{R}}{100}$
\end_inset

 are presented.
 We confirm the intuition suggested at the final paragraph of the previous
 section, that for equal coupling strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}=g_{R}$
\end_inset

the term induced by the diagonal coupling overcomes the counter-rotating
 contribution.
 Both terms share the same linear scaling with their respective coupling
 strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

, so naturally as we decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

, the squared transition amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a_{nn}^{+-}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is suppressed proportionally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This simple linear scaling is slightly modified in the detuned case, in
 which the slopes change around 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}\approx\frac{\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{a}\right)}{2\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 An example for a strong detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{a}=0.8\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(b).
 We find that in this case the contribution of both perturbative terms is
 suppressed with respect to the resonant result.
 However, for relatively small coupling strengths 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}<4\times10^{-3}\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 the terms corresponding to the asymmetric contribution still dominate over
 the ones due to the counter-rotating Hamiltonian even for reduced 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}\approx0.01g_{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

