\end_inset

.
 Results are shown on resonance 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}=\omega_{a}$
\end_inset

 (a,c,e) and in a detuned case 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega_{c}-\omega_{a}\right)/\omega_{c}=0.2$
\end_inset

 (b,d,f).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:amplitudes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
For a wide range of the coupling strengths, the squared transition amplitudes
 induced by the part of the perturbation related to the asymmettry dominate
 over those originating from the counter-rotating term.
 However, the transition probability in a 
\begin_inset Formula $p+1$
\end_inset

 dimensional space is rescaled by the density of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\left(E_{i}^{\iota}-E_{f}^{\phi}\right)^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in 3D the low-energy transitions will be suppressed, while the
 high-energy component from the counter-rotating contribution to the Hamiltonian
 will be relatively increased.
 This rescaling is observed both in the resonant and off resonant case in
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(c,d).
 In the off-resonant case we note that the for equal coupling strengths
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}=g_{R}$
\end_inset

 the terms that origin at the diagonal-coupling still dominate over the
 counter-rotating ones, despite the latter are by far more energetically
 favorable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Rescaling of the transition probabilities between the one-dimentional [Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(a,b)] and three-dimentional cases [Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(c,d)] demonstrates the possibility of tailoring the output by density of
 states engineering.
 To highlight this point further, we insert the entire system in a single-mode
 cavity for which we assume a Lorentzian density of states, centered at
 the low-energy transition frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathrm{ext}}=E_{ii}^{+-(0)}$
\end_inset

 and of full-width at half-maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\mathrm{ext}}=10^{-4}\omega_{c}.$
\end_inset

 A cavity with comparable parameters can be realized in photonic crystals
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lu2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that provide 1D or 2D photonic environments, in whispering-gallery-mode
 resonators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogt2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 or, with smaller quality factors, using metamaterials 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zografopoulos2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Here, the cavity is tailored to emphasize the strength of the low-energy
 transition 
\begin_inset Formula $|n^{+}\rangle\rightarrow|n^{-}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for the cost of suppressing other transitions.
 Indeed, as demonstrated in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:amplitudes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

(e,f), this is successful both in the resonant case and for the strongly
 detuned one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
For the above analysis we have selected only one exemplary transition of
 the Jaynes-Cummings, diagonal-coupling and counter-rotating groups, correspondi
ng to different-color arrows in Fig.
 
