\begin_layout Subsection
Validity of the perturbative approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we verify the range of coupling strengths for which the
 perturbative approach applied in the main text is justified.
 Naturally, the condition is that the perturbation corrections to the energies
 are small with respect to the energy differences, and that the perturbation
 series converge both for the perturbed energies and the states.
 This is not the case around the energy crossings, where some of the series
 terms diverge.
 To identify the applicability range of the approach, we therefore perform
 two tests: we verify 1) preservation of the energy structure and 2) the
 normalization of the states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preservation of the energy structure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of energy levels is preserved if the coupling strength 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 is small enough to avoid energy level crossings.
 Otherwise, a level crossing gives rise to divergent resonances which are
 not physical but they are artifacts of the theory: the energy differences
 in the denominators in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ket_2nd_order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) vanish and the expression diverges.
 The positions of the energy crossings depend on the initial state: in the
 following examples we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $|10^{+}\rangle$
\end_inset

 as the initial state, for which the first relevant crossing appears between
 the energies of states 
\begin_inset Formula $|10^{-}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|9^{+}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Its position depends on the atom-cavity detuning: on resonance 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{a}=\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 the crossing appears around 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}/\omega_{a}=0.15$
\end_inset

, and blue-shifts as the cavity red-shifts from the atomic transition.
 That dependence is visualized in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:validity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that for a strong blue detuning of the cavity 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\omega_{a}}{\omega_{c}}\leq0.5$
\end_inset

, the level ordering in the ladder structure from Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is reshuffled and the analysis in this regime would have to be done independent
ly.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename detuning.eps
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The black line corresponds to the position of the first level crossing in
 function of the relative energy of the atomic system and the cavity mode.
 The figure corresponds to the initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $|10^{+}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The black point corresponds to the first crossing in the left panel of
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:energy_10_resonance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.

\color blue
 
\color inherit
The structure of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is preserved in the part of parameter space shaded in grey.
 and the validity of our model is a subarea in blue where we consider the
 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 of the energy difference without any coupling (
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}=0$
\end_inset

).
 This analysis does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:validity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preservation of the ladder structure is just the necessary condition for
 the following analysis.
 In practice, the denominators in the coefficients in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ket_2nd_order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can get arbitrarily large in close proximity of the crossing point, i.e.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R,\mathrm{crossing}}-g_{R}<\delta$
\end_inset

.
 This condition defines the parameter region for which the ladder structure
 is correctly represented in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:energy_10_resonance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and yields that the coupling strength must be strictly smaller than a
 threshold value 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R,\mathrm{crossing}}-\delta$
\end_inset

.
 We deem the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 to be safe if the energy difference of the states responsible for the first
 crossing (in the illustrated example: 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{10}^{-(0)}-E_{9}^{+(0)}$
\end_inset

) for a given coupling strength 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 is larger than 10% of its value for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}=0$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E_{10}^{-(0)}\left(g_{R}\right)-E_{9}^{+(0)}\left(g_{R}\right) & \leq\frac{E_{10}^{-(0)}\left(0\right)-E_{9}^{+(0)}\left(0\right)}{10},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and the equality is achieved for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}=g_{R,\mathrm{crossing}}-\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Safe parameter space defined in this way is shaded in blue in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:validity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preservation of state normalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state norm is approximately preserved for a set of model parameters
 sufficiently away from an energy crossing.
 For the cases investigated in the main manuscript, the first energy crossing
 among the investigated states appears for those corresponding to the highest
 manifold.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:norm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we plot the norm of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|10_{+}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 in function of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{S}=g_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A clear divergence appears for the coupling strengths approaching 
\begin_inset Formula $0.14\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

, which results from a crossing involving higher manifolds, in this case
 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\left(14\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The vertical line in the figure indicates the limit for the coupling strengths
 considered in the main text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename normstate.eps
	width 60text%
	rotateOrigin centerTop

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Norm of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|10_{+}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 For coupling strengths around and above 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}>0.1\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

the norm deviates from 1, which is an indication of breakdown of the perturbatio
n theory.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:norm"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In conclusion we have applied the 2nd order perturbation theory to investigate
 the emission properties of a two-level system coupled to a single-mode
 electromagnetic field, including interaction channels based on the Jaynes-Cummi
ngs, counter-rotating and asymmetry-related contributions.
 In the electric-dipole interaction mechanism, the first two arise from
 the coupling of the field mode with the induced transition dipole moment,
 the latter requires a permanent dipole characterizing the system's eigenstates.
 Light-matter coupling with permanent dipoles gives birth to additional
 emission peaks.
 We have demonstrated that even though at some frequencies the asymmetry-related
 contribution is weak in relative terms, the signal-to-noise ratio is comparable
 for all emission peaks.
 Moreover, the relative strengths of the emission peaks can be modified
 with a suitable photonic environment, as we have discussed for 1D systems
 and for a Lorentzian cavity.
 In the latter example we have shown that for cavity parameters that lie
 well within the range of experimental capabilities, the asymmetry-related
 emission channel may even dominate in absolute terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future research: the role of the environment and canonical derivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the analysis of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Hamiltonian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we solve the problem of the divergence in the longitudinal component of
 the Green tensor propagator as discussed after Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ImGT"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, using the spatial extension of the wavefunctions which provide a natural
 regularization of the integral momenta of the quantum system surrounded
 by a continuum dispersive medium.
 However we can also solve the problem considering a point-like quantum
 system and regularize the continuum dispersive medium such that at higher
 frequencies the coupling with the quantum system is vanishing.
 Indeed, at this regime the theory doesn't work because the discretization
 of the atoms in the medium becomes relevant.
 In the following, we suggest how to implement this idea.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

We implemented the phenomenological effective Hamiltonian in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, starting from first principles of QED we can rewrite the creation
 and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the noise polarization
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vogel2006,Czech_red_book"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)=i\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\epsilon_{0}}{\pi}\epsilon_{I}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)}\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{I}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)=\mathrm{Im}\epsilon\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The quantity rise up in the expression of the polarization due to the presence
 of the 
\emph on
bound 
\emph default
charge in the macroscopic treatment of Maxwell equation, in the expression
 of the polarization as a transfer function of the medium in the presence
 of an electric field
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buhmann2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{P}_{b}\left(\boldsymbol{r},t\right)= & \epsilon_{0}\int\int_{0}^{\infty}\chi\left(\boldsymbol{s},t\right)\boldsymbol{E}\left(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{s},t-\tau\right)d\tau d^{3}s+\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{r},t\right)\\
\tilde{\boldsymbol{P}}_{b}\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right) & =\epsilon_{0}\epsilon\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{E}}\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)-1\right)+\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)=1+\chi\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and the latter equation is the Fourier transform of the former.
 The susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 of the medium is the 
\emph on
response function
\emph default
, and it is convoluted in space and time with the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that there not exists an analogous term 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}_{N}$
\end_inset

, in classical physics where we do not applied the same concept of vacuum.
 Nonetheless, according to fluctuation–dissipation theorem of classical
 statistical physics [2, 3], the fluctuation spectrum of a physical quantity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 can be related to the imaginary part of the susceptibility.
 Denoting classical fluctuations by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}=\boldsymbol{P}_{N}-\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle _{\mathrm{cl}}$
\end_inset

 (the noise terms vanish on the classical average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle _{\mathrm{cl}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buhmann2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) the fluctuation and dissipation theorem (Fourier transform only in time)
 reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}^{*}\left(\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime},\omega^{\prime}\right)\right\rangle _{\mathrm{cl}}=\frac{k_{B}T}{\pi\omega}\epsilon_{0}\mathrm{Im}\chi\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)\delta\left(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime}\right)\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{\prime}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

: Boltzmann constant; 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

: temperature).
 The imaginary parts of the response functions determine whether the medium
 is absorbing or amplifying.
 We only consider absorbing media for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 has a positive imaginary part.
 The above equations thus reveal the intrinsic connection between fluctuations
 and absorption: fluctuations are necessarily present in any absorbing system
 at non-zero temperature.
 Note that the classical fluctuations vanish in the zero-temperature limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hands, for a system prepare in a quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 of an appropriate Hilbert space, the quantum average observable is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle =\left\langle \psi|\boldsymbol{P}_{N}|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where now 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}_{N}$
\end_inset

 is an operator acting on such Hilbert space.
 Its quantum fluctuations can be calculated according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left(\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right)^{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle ^{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}=\boldsymbol{P}_{N}-\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then we have that the noise polarization vanishes on its grounds state
 average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \boldsymbol{P}_{N}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and its fluctuations ruled by the fluctation-dissipation theorem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mathcal{S}\left(\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)\Delta\boldsymbol{P}_{N}^{\dagger}\left(\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime},\omega^{\prime}\right)\right)\right\rangle =\frac{\hbar}{2\pi}\epsilon_{0}\mathrm{Im}\chi\left(\boldsymbol{r},\omega\right)\delta\left(\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r}^{\prime}\right)\delta\left(\omega-\omega^{\prime}\right)\label{eq:diss-fluc_q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\left(ab\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(ab+ba\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes a symmetrised operator product.
 Note that the average thermal energy 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 appearing in the classical fluctuation-dissipation theorem has been replaced
 with the quantum ground-state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 of a bosonic system.
 The use of a noise polarisation with a spectrum governed by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diss-fluc_q"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is known as Rytov theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rytov_1989"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, it lies at the heart of Lifshitz’ s famous calculation of the Casimir
 force 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lifshitz1992theory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The imaginary part of the longitudinal Green tensor propagator for a non
 local susceptibility in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:G"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Im}\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\parallel}(\boldsymbol{q},\omega)=\frac{c^{2}}{\omega^{2}}\frac{q_{j}q_{k}}{|\boldsymbol{q}|^{2}}\frac{\epsilon_{I}\left(\boldsymbol{q},\omega\right)}{\left|\epsilon\left(\boldsymbol{q},\omega\right)\right|^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the relation of the permettivity we propose our model of suscptibility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)=1+\chi\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)=1+\chi_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{k},\omega\right)=\left(\chi_{0,R}+i\chi_{0,I}\right)\exp\left(-\frac{k^{2}}{k_{M}^{2}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This provide a convergent integral of with a cut-off paramenter 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{M}$
\end_inset

, as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Im}\tilde{G}_{jk}^{\parallel}\left(\bm{\rho},\omega\right)=\frac{2\pi c^{2}}{\left(2\pi\omega\right)^{2}}\frac{\Im\chi_{0}\left(0,\omega\right)}{\left|1+\chi_{0}\left(0,\omega\right)\right|^{2}}\frac{2k_{M}^{3}}{3\sqrt{\pi}}\delta_{ij}\left(1+O\left(\rho^{4}\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\rho}$
\end_inset

is the relative distance between the positive charge at the origin and the
 relative negative charge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In the end, one should be rigorous to derive the commutation relation of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 starting from the Lagrangian and applied the Fano diagonalization on the
 Hamiltonian obtained by the Legendre transform similarly to Ref 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Huttner1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

